  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Enclosure is the process of converting commons — collectively governed shared resources — into private property. The English enclosure acts of the fifteenth through nineteenth centuries are the paradigmatic case: parliamentary legislation and landlord action converted common pastures, forests, and fields into privately owned parcels, displacing the rural population from the land that sustained them. This dispossession created a class of people who, lacking independent access to subsistence, had no choice but to sell their labor for wages.\n",
  "name": "Enclosure",
